Full-model runtime boundary audit
Date: 2026-07-20 UTC
Scope: tt/model.py, tt/generator.py, tt/multichip_decoder.py

Optimized model runtime
- Embedding, all 40 decoder layers, final RMS norm, TP4 vocabulary head,
  local-top-k selection, global candidate exchange, and token writeback execute
  as TTNN device operations.
- Decode retains the accepted TP4 1x4 decoder, BFP4/LoFi dense policy,
  BF16 residual/activation policy, BFP8 paged KV cache, persistent BFP8
  asynchronous all-reduce decode output, BF16 prefill all-reduce output, and
  the accepted inter-layer stacked residual layout.
- There is no PyTorch operation, host tensor conversion, host argmax, or
  full-logits readback in MistralSmall24BFullModel.prefill_forward,
  decode_forward, sample_split, or the split sampling traces.
- PyTorch use in model.py is confined to checkpoint loading, validation, and
  one-time device-weight construction.

Generator cache and request state
- Caller-owned and generator-owned cache paths use the same direct per-rank
  paged K/V tensors. There is no replicated or host KV-cache fallback.
- Explicit fixed-slot page tables are normalized once at the request boundary.
  The persistent trace page-table buffer is copied only when its value changes.
- Signed current-position and unsigned rotary-position tensors are persistent,
  device-resident trace inputs. Both are incremented inside the model trace;
  inactive signed rows remain -1.
- Reset zeroes device caches in place and retains weights, persistent buffers,
  and compiled traces. A prior request's traces are released only immediately
  before a shape-dependent new prefill; trace-bound addresses are never reused
  while active.

Sampling boundaries
- Optimized sampling_mode="device" uses Sampling1D local top-k split sampling.
  With k=1, p=0, temperature=1 it is semantically greedy. The sampled token is
  written directly into the persistent next-token tensor consumed by the next
  model-trace replay. There is no host token feedback copy.
- One sampled-token readback per step is solely the public returned-token
  observation boundary. It is not used to feed the next device step.
- sampling_mode="host" is an explicit compatibility path. Only this path reads
  full logits and calls torch.argmax; it is not used for optimized token-out
  correctness or performance claims.
- Teacher forcing retains split model/sampler traces, but explicitly copies the
  reference token after observing each model prediction, as required by the
  readiness callback contract.

Long-prompt boundary
- Public prefill owns non-aligned padding, logical prompt lengths, output
  slicing, position selection, cache fill, and inactive rows. A 576-token
  optimized prefill window is followed by device decoder cache-fill steps for
  longer prompts. Host loop construction occurs during prompt ingestion only,
  not in measured autoregressive token feedback.

Rejected fallbacks
- Single-chip execution: rejected; the constructor requires a 1x4 TP mesh.
- Replicated decoder weights or KV cache: rejected; rank-local TP weights and
  rank-local paged KV heads remain mandatory.
- Host-side decoder/language head: rejected.
- Full-logits greedy decode: retained only as named host compatibility mode.
- Common force-argmax sampler: comparison-only; rejected for the optimized path
  after the on-device semantic and latency comparison.
